Inflation in Europe has fallen on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 euro area countries was higher than forecast, following an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 per cent was recorded, the Statistical Office of the European Community located in Luxembourg indicated.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, reported Bloomberg.
Contrary to US, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the direct interest rate by saying that the decline in interest rates, along with the growth in commodity prices and the fall in the unemployment rate, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two per cent.
According to an analyst, the ECB's Catch 22 is: "dissuade" inflation in order to avoid having to intervene later on.
In Germany, the rate of inflation of 3.3 per cent has been a record over the last 12 years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has gone off because of the rapid increase in food and energy prices.
Quotas for the cereal market have increased by 88 per cent and the soy price has also reached its highest value since 1973.
Food oil and dairy prices also increased considerably in 2007.
This year, the world price of oil increased by 52 percent and last month a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will increase from 2.1 this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, the rate of inflation over 12 months is around 3 per cent, however, for the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 per cent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to decrease the policy rate twice in 2008.
Gallup indicates a government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) supporters increased significantly at the beginning of December. Thus, since 2002, it has currently had the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Institute of Survey) has never seen such low socialist support, that is 13 per cent.
For faithful voters, the difference would represent more than two thirds (71 per cent) of support for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party) due to the greater determination of the opposition voters.
According to the survey, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two per cent throughout the population.
On some faithful voters to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 per cent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate compared to the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who considered the country's economic situation to be particularly serious has never been so high, reaching 41 per cent and, according to 46 per cent additional, the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic prospects of spring and last summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population is forecast to increase and only one tenth are forecast to improve the situation.
In December of this year, 71 per cent of the respondents, i.e. a majority never seen in Gallup's previous surveys, found that the Prime Minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 per cent do not trust the Prime Minister at all and 27 per cent do not trust the President of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of change in the political situation is the proportion of society that believes that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be addressed without a change in government.
While after last October's riots, 35 per cent of respondents wanted the government and the Prime Minister to remain in office, the current rate is only 20 per cent. The relative majority (33 per cent) believes that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
On the question of the intention to vote, 60 per cent of respondents said that they would certainly go to vote and the additional 20 per cent said that they would probably go to vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election next Sunday", only 55 per cent of respondents would certainly participate and 15 per cent of respondents would probably participate. According to current intentions, the result of the referendum would be no doubt.
74 per cent would say no to enrolment fees in higher education, 79 per cent would say no to consultation fees, and 84 per cent would say no to hospitalization fees.
When we look at only the same proportions among those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, respectively 81, 84 and 89 per cent of voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospitalization fees.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by nearly twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs commercial triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 per cent last year, unlike this year's VAT rate did not increase.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (daily economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas Cart also increased by 16 per cent on average, an increase in value of significantly more than a thousand forints appeared in all hypermarkets.
Prices, "which had already flown" in the major food stores last December, did not increase sharply compared to the previous high base.
However, consumers are of course shocked to see that items purchased significantly below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The Daily Carteier in hypermarkets surveyed exceeded the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints by 91 forints at least.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
The prices of Unicum and live fish remained almost unchanged last year, however, prices of turkey, walnut and parrot increased sharply.
In the stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data from KSH (Institut Central des Statistiques) but, at Auchan, one kilo of bread was found in 139 forints only.
Competition has not reduced the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the two-litre registered bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the registered bottle including.
It prevents this year, in terms of Daily Cart, Auchan was the cheapest and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora has increased the price of its Daily Shopping Cart by 15 per cent while Tesco and Auchan have increased it by about 18 per cent and 18 per cent respectively.
By comparing the most expensive basket last year and the cheapest basket this year, we find a difference of 12 per cent while the difference between the cheapest basket last year and the cheapest basket this year is 21 per cent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices rose by an average of 1,206 forints, while at the same time knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noticeable in last year's Christmas prices.
This process made trade perplexed, the hypermarkets could not clearly determine which margin to apply to products as long as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader is ill-calculated for the rotation of a product, he may lose a big profit on the margin appropriate to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the rise in daily basket prices has changed so excessively that the most expensive basket was more than 1,720 forints than in 2006, whereas the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not too excessive since the most expensive basket value was more than 1,630 forints than last year's, and the least expensive prices also increased by 1,284 forints.
Close to the two Christmas seasons, we observed a catastrophic price increase, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumer goods increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH's data: for some basic supplies, the Institute of Statistics observed an increase in prices of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and egg.)
According to the daily Cartier of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers occupy a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have succeeded in making the brutal price increase accepted by multinationals as well.
In the commercial gold triangle, the hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
Based on our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at the prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-term food from pallets.
Wednesday morning important tails formed the caisses of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, turnover is less important in the province, many multinationals complain about the survey companies not even reaching the planned turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals do the economy on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, were recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overrun of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the chief physician of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also do the economy on disinfectants
A MRSA infection has not long been diagnosed at the János Hospital trauma department.
Antibiotic resistant bacteria were detected in a hospitalized man following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, a similar infection occurred at the same site.
The injured person from a serious car accident left the hospital but shortly after he had to return because of an MRSA infection, and since then the doctors have not been able to perform an important operation because of the bacteria found in his body.
Until December 10 this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, Chief Physician of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Knowing that it is the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
Approximately two-thirds of the infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. by staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacilline.
One third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SAs (such as angina, amygdalites, skin infections, traumatic infections) react well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used overly or inappropriately, the bacteria, which react well to antibiotics, will develop a well-resistant antibiotic bacteria that will rapidly proliferate in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged immune system malfunction, this bacteria may cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or septicaemia, on elderly, small-weight or impaired organisms.
According to the János hospital director, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the hospital's daily routine.
Above all, the infection should not be confused with the epidemic, it is not possible to find MRSA only the one or the other one, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the nursing staff put rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics suitable for treating them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they carry MRSA, however the infection cannot always be avoided.
Sample sampling is not in the mode
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not conducive to preventing the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and elderly homes, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients carrying MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases arise only if MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief physician at the epidemiological centre.
The European Union has strong recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the cure of certain infections and infections.
Efforts must be made to target antibiotic therapy, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and basic care," said Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals do the economy on disinfectants
There is scientific evidence that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical staff.
It is therefore essential to wash hands, put gloves and protective masks, but important gaps are also detected in hospitals in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other, while in the event of an epidemic, the sick should be removed from each other by a minimum of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in difficult financial situations, save on disinfectants, lack nurses, the sick are many, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are observed, the number of infections is lower in a demonstrable way or the spread of the pathogen can be blocked.
Governmental Project against MRSAs
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant spending on social security funds, which is why we are fighting against this infection everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSAs.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) highlights among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The Commissioner, the author of a fatal accident, was not drunk
The official finding on the fatal accident caused by the Commissioner of the 22nd district was made.
It may be excluded that the commissioner of the 22nd district, who had resigned from his post since then, who crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have led to drunkness or dizziness, announced Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman of the Public Ministry of the capital after the relative finding was established.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation, which has already found that the former Commissioner did not consume alcohol before driving.
Last Tuesday, the former chief of the 22nd district police crashed a 55-year-old man who was faced with him when he turned, with his personal car, on the street Kossuth Lajos of the 22nd district. The man wanted to cross the road by not passing through the pedestrian crossing.
