€400 million extra for infrastructure
János Veres, Minister of Finance of Hungary, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three €400 million credit line agreements in Budapest on Friday to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environment projects to be implemented from the Cohesion Fund, of which a credit contract worth EUR 100 million has already been signed by the parties. This time, the signed contract concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The agreement on the appropriation of EUR 150 million also covers the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, while the remaining EUR 150 million will be used later, following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a 50 million euro contract for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope primarily as part of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the metro line 4 project was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would discuss the possible modification of the initial contract once Hungary completed the details of metro financing with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has granted a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its loans according to the EURIBOR interest rate, with a grace period of 8 years and without a commitment commission.
Bulgaria, EU real estate market paradise
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of the whole of Europe has been directed towards this Balkan country, which has not been mentioned in the past.
What, or who buys in this EU market that is always the cheapest but will quickly become the cheapest?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
At present, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most popular target in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and houses by the cheap sea.
In the mountains, the most popular areas are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Sables d'Or", the "Côte du sun", the former Sozopol and Nessebar, but more and more of them are looking for a building in the Kavarna and Balcik region as well.
According to analysts from Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse the interest of investors and they are also increasingly buying in the cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, offers attractive opportunities as well, business and office areas promise the highest rate of depreciation.
Bulgaria is on the way to becoming one of Europe's most attractive golf paradise, making it a priority destination after the summer and winter seasons, also in the other two seasons of the year.
The more vigilant investors already buy many, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are at the same time seeking to change their lives and lifestyles.
Most buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the Black Sea and in the most famous ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, according to Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who intend to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old detached houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication opportunities, the proximity of a large city, shops and generally that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of secondary residences (since last December Bulgaria is ranked among the first 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is composed of commercial investors who are looking forward to achieving medium- or long-term added value.
The price of the capital's buildings is constantly rising as demand increases.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last five years, they have increased by 21 per cent each year.
The increase in real estate prices essentially exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarians
According to Gábor Fodor, Minister of the Environment and Waters, the professional meetings end on Tuesday, however, Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap to define efforts to be made after the Kyoto Protocol emission reduction period until 2012.
At the moment, intense discussions are being held on this issue between developing and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, for the time being, they did not want to discuss exact figures, but were prepared to sign an agreement on reducing greenhouse gas emissions from 25 to 40 per cent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries are committed to providing financial and technological assistance to those countries in need, excluding emission reductions.
An agreement was also signed on aid to developing countries.
The support fund set out in the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a board of 16 members, probably within the framework of the United Nations Global Environment Fund (GEF), Piac és Profit (Market and Profit).
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister of the Environment and Waters, confirms the EU's ambition to maintain its role as an admiral vessel in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU was committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 compared to the 1990 level, regardless of the success of the signing of the “After 2012 Agreement”, and was prepared to reduce them to 30 per cent if the other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also prepared to take appropriate commitments to meet their responsibilities and capacities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the Kyoto Protocol signatory countries had a total reduction of 5.2 per cent, and all 15 EU members at that time made a commitment of 8 per cent less.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent compared to the 1985-87 level, our country will fulfil its commitment, recalls the press release from the Ministry of the Environment.
The issue is great in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, the commitments below the Kyoto Protocol's values would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, the need for which was stressed in the new IPCC report, the international scientific body, which obtained the UN Nobel Peace Prize to deal with climate change.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and the increase in average earth temperature of more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
The British army recruits on YouTube
The British Army units, on the video-sharing site, provide recordings of their operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with a view to becoming popular.
Firstly, the British Air Force (RAF) has been passionate about YouTube: the special units in Afghanistan have been loading video sequences on Taliban operations since March 2006, and the BBC has announced this.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are controlled at the Air Force Operations Headquarters in Kandahar and are then transferred to Londrès or the compatriots charge them on the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
Air force soldiers have already spent 139 sequences on the net by this route and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered under the name of Defenceheadquarters in the spring of 2007 and provides videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Commonwealth Office and the international peacekeeping forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were put on the net to recruit, and according to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to make the public aware of the real objectives of the military's presence abroad.
The propaganda published in this way costs virtually nothing in relation to the usual advertising of recruitment on television, to the BBC Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant. On the other hand, it also inevitably carries a political message as it justifies in a special form the soundness of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game
The army is upset because, apart from the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos have passed on the sharing site, which also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocriteed, the officers do not avoid talking about losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
In fact, many videos had already gone over the net showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were being carried out on a real mission, but the British army has only recently taken care of loading these videos.
The Americans recruit a little differently using the America's Army shooting game downloadable for free. In this game the player can place himself directly in the place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
