The forces of the mega strike gather
The unions of the League and the National Association of Workers' Councils will be their strike commission on Friday, which will be responsible for coordinating the strike on an indefinite basis from Monday.
On Saturday, a general protest assembly will be held and on Monday, on the day of the final vote on the Health Insurance Act, the strike will begin.
This action will certainly cause significant traffic congestion as rail traffic will be almost completely stopped and BKV employees (public transport company) will also strike until 1 p.m.
The Unions of the League will see the details of their Monday strike on Friday afternoon with the National Workers' Council Association.
The LIGA-MOSZ strike commission will also be set up as the Monday action coordinator.
On Saturday, a general protest assembly will be held and, starting on Monday, organizations joining the strike will stop work indefinitely if they fail to reach an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, from the day of the vote in parliament on the Health Insurance Act, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not comply with the Health Insurance Act, the unions will immediately withdraw the appeal to strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, strike commissions will meet and decide how to proceed.
According to the National Assembly's Monday agenda, it is likely that the vote on the Health Insurance Act will take place only late in the evening or even at night.
As a result of the strike scheduled for Monday, important traffic plugs are planned: railways will stop work indefinitely and during the morning part of the public transport to Budapest and more than half of Volán companies are at risk of being stopped.
At the same time, at different points in the country, half of the track will also be blocked.
Many trade unions and civil organizations have joined the call for the strike, and the list of them is constantly updated on the site of the League.
Some organizations reported that the strike was indeterminate, while others reported a temporary stoppage of work.
Until Thursday afternoon the MÁV (Hungarian Iron Chemins) and the Free Union of Railways (VDSZSZ) have not succeeded in finding agreement on the minimum services, but, as Christmas holidays approach, more and more are taking the train.
According to current communications, public transport in Budapest will strike from the beginning of service until 1 p.m., Budapest airport between 7 a.m. and 9 a.m., the Industrial Unions of Electricity and Thermal Energy of the League will strike for four hours, the Union of Professors and the Democratic Union of Professors called for a strike for two hours and two hours at 8 a.m. respectively.
The National Association of Physicians will strike across the country, the Union of Health and Social Employees (EDDSZ) attached to the SZEF will make a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four claims made by the League requires the government to withdraw its proposal for health reform and submit a new approach to social debate.
The second claim requires that the new method of calculating retirement to be implemented from next year be introduced in several stages.
The third claim is a guarantee of retirement before the legal age, which would allow the functions that deserve it before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Union of Railways (VDSZSZ), linked to the Unions of the League, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport concerning secondary rail lines and waiting for another proposal.
Political Capital: The Hungarian Guard has increased the risk country
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital (Risk Analysis Division), the activity of the Hungarian Guard, which was formed last August, with the support of Jobbik Magyarszágért Mozgalom (Movement pour eine plus Hungary) increases the political risk of Hungary and the region in several aspects.
In its "risk warning", society points out that, in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is already that "in the short term aggressive ethnic clashes may occur as a result of the worsening ethnic tension already existing between the Zigan and non-Zigan population of Hungary".
The research institute added that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy likely to cause this situation is the main reason.
As they say, this is due to one of the main shortcomings of Hungarian political actors: "public actors have passed the public debate on the Roma affair to representatives of radical and extreme political groupings who have based a political strategy on the dispute between the Tzigans and the Hungarians".
The problem gets worse, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are strengthened and the arrival of aggressive conflicts is more likely, they say.
However, according to the research institute, due to the increased attention of the Hungarian and international media, the activity of the Hungarian Guard "has significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, in particular regarding confidence in the country's stability and democratic maturity".
They recall that, as a result of greater publicity given to the reorganization of Hungarian right-wing radical and extreme groups since the fall of 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007, calling themselves the "National Self-Defense Association".
"The common feature of these gatherings is that they define themselves as a civil organization when they publicly declare the preparation of their members for defence missions (disasters, national defence, defence of order), armed if necessary, in addition, by referring to the inability of the police, of the army, that is, of the state," they added.
They pointed out that everything was in line with the method that, based on the harshness of the society of politics and the parties, seeks to disguise different political ambitions from a civil point of view.
The emphasis on the civil character and the status of association therefore serves only to avoid the legal pitfalls in the registration of such associations in court, but they also constitute a political strategy.
The analysis indicates that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a factor that also increases the risk of neighbourhood relations.
