A Heavy Memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million records, stored on 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were so far only available for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and nominally, at the request of an ex-victim or his right-holders.
The eleven states in charge of their management, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed in May 2006 to open them up to researchers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Relevant information
Historians' access to Bad Arolsen will enable them to conduct research "including the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced workers", says Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, opposed the opening to the public of these nominal documents because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the supposed homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The records of the Gestapo concentration camps or arrest warrants had been gathered after war for a practical purpose: to find the civilians deported or subjected to compulsory labour and, possibly, to provide proof of their detention, in order to open the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to wait for these documents," said Dr. Wolfgang Benz, Director of the Anti-Semitism Research Centre at the Technische Universität in Berlin in 2006.
