Venus is the infernal twinle of the Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus looks more like the Earth than we thought so far: the European Space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind turbines at the poles, similar to those appearing on Earth in winter.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that there is light on Venus.
Today, the European "Venus Express" probe has demonstrated this - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the limit of the atmosphere: lightnings on Venus burst to a height of about 56 kilometres of cloud cloud, says Christopher Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous cyprine theory, lightning would have revealed life on Earth: thunder would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case with Venus: "If life existed, it must have been at a very old time in history," says Sean Solomon of the "Carnegie Institution" in Washington, D.C.
Today there should be little living things on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about 100 times denser than on Earth, sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus is perhaps the infernal twinle of the Earth, but it remains a twinle," said Russel.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and dimensions, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in Venusian research, since no probe was in progress for the exploration of this planet since the 1990s.
In the opinion of researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several articles of "Nature" do not only highlight the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the common points with the Earth of our neighbouring planet are more numerous than supposed at first.
In addition to the wind turbines already known at the north pole, the researchers found a cloud turbine at the south pole, which is running much faster.
The phenomenon recalls the currents of air in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmoca.
The second solar system planet has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The world that is qualified as a star of the evening or morning revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much slower on itself: one Venezuelan day lasts 243 terrien days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, does not recall the Earth, scientists assume that the two planets were formed under similar conditions.
On both sides, the water was accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has fixed on Earth in the form of carbonate, it is on Venus most of the atmosphere.
