It's not the Warhols caisses.
The one who connects the concepts of Sweden and wooden caisse, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At this time, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol's list of works.
A large part of the eighty-nine "Type Stockholm" Brillo-Boxs listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of the Brillo-Boxes of the year 1968 by Andy Warhol, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm today leads to a disillusioning result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", of which the former director of the Pontus Hulten museum presented in 1995 at Moderna Museet, are copies - as well as a large part of the other hundreds of Brillo-Boxen of "Type Stockholm", which circulate on the international art market.
The ancient history is intertwined, a disconcerting chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes, based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" powder soap cartons.
An exhibition of his work at Moderna Museet in 1968 - with the agreement of Warhol - presented hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These were not (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cartoning factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exposure samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exposed to the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time today speak of about fifteen wooden caisses, which at the time would have entered the history of art and auctions, as the original Brillo-Boxes authorized by Andy Warhol, with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them reached over $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum wrongly claimed, later on, that about one hundred wooden caisses had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, that Warhol would then have handed over to him.
Indeed, the 105 caisses de Hultén were produced in Malmö in 1990 only, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
On that date, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, curator-in-chief of Moderna Museet, examined three other Swedish private collections alongside the museum's six Brillo-Boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their stratified panels were first printed and punched, and then applied with a brush of white oil paint.
The texture of the copies that date from 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the painting was directly applied without a background layer on the stratified panels, using a painting roller - moreover it is not an oil painting, but an acrylic.
"These caisses have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes", says the director of Moderna Museet Lars Nittve: "If the "Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board" in New York does not come to another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six caisses in its collection as copies/exposure material."
Already in July the Authentication Board of course announced that it would investigate the "hard charges" that will be raised in the case of soap boxes in powder.
But since then we've had an inexorable silence.
